DescriptionText.En: Every captain has their humble beginnings. Fly, shoot, repair, and spot dummy ships and experiment with different ship loadouts. With a variety of hotkeys at your disposal, you can simulate many combat situations and test your abilities.

FullDescriptionText.En:
— FLY! Get a feel for the wheel and experiment with the helm tools to perform fancy maneuvers.
— SHOOT! Guns are effective against different parts, so practice aiming for the hull, balloon, guns, and engines, and try different ammo and weapons loadouts.
— REPAIR! Test out the different repair and fire-fighting tools when your ship takes damage, and use a buff tool when it's in good shape. Keep hull armor up to protect your core health.
— SPOT! Mark enemy ships with your spyglass (right click to zoom, left click to spot) to keep tabs on them and tell friend from foe.
[TAB] to view teams list; [M] to view local map; set ship priority: [F1] Normal, [F2] Offense, [F3] Defense

DescriptionText.En: Some disputes are not about survival. Some are just a show of might. The Dust brought fierce winds Combined with the obelisk-like ribs of old vessels of destruction, battles fought in this edge of the desert are only for those with cunning... or nothing to lose.

FullDescriptionText.En: Some scores can only be settled in combat. Choose a second and meet your foes on the field of battle to duke it out once and for all. May the best team win.

DescriptionText.En: Some disputes are not about survival. Some are just a show of might. The Dust brought fierce winds Combined with the obelisk-like ribs of old vessels of destruction, battles fought in this edge of the desert are only for those with cunning... or nothing to lose.

DescriptionText.En: Merchants look at two things when deciding on a route: distance and chance of an ambush.  While the Red Canyon is the shortest distance between the Yesha Empire and Anglean Republic, it is also littered with chasms and gullies—happy hunting, safe travels!

FullDescriptionText.En: A favored trade route for merchants making the run north from the Yesha Empire up to Cusichaca on the coast, the Red Canyons are also a prime spot for ambush, and many an unwary captain has been waylaid with a hold full of goods among the red rocks and ruins in this desolate stretch of chasms and gullies. The Canyons also offer the shortest flight path between the Empire and the Republic, although the region's hardscrabble hamlets are slim pickings and Anglean Gatherers out on a raiding mission can find easier targets than the well-defended cities of the Yesha heartland.

DescriptionText.En: King Greger’s influence, of the Fjord Baronies, is weak in this icy stretch north of Glowwater Bay. While an important foothold in Firnfeld, the area is rife with pirates and marauders that often come into contact with patrol ship from the Baronites. Cold cloudy combat climbs.

FullDescriptionText.En: North of Glowwater Bay, the Chattering Fjords seasonal melt gives way to permafrost and a coast cluttered year-round with ice. The Fjord Baronies extended its territory north into this beautiful but forbidding land with the siege and capture of the Navinstaak military base almost thirty years ago, gaining a foothold in icebound Firnfeld and a new remote holding to secure. King Greger's influence is weakly felt this far from the Kingseat, and though patrols from Glowwater and Northlake make their rounds through the territory, in truth this icy stretch of coast is rife with bandits and pirates ready to tussle with any unwary explorer or insufficiently armed patrol ship, and conflicts are common in the region.

DescriptionText.En: The Fjord Baronies control many industrial assets, including the Blackcliff Metal Works. Baronites must be vigilant while transporting their labor forces from factory to factory because brigands wait for the chance to plunder their rich ore and steel.

FullDescriptionText.En: The Blackcliff Metal Works are one of the Fjords' key industrial assets, processing the iron ores mined in the Eastern Ridge into the steel and iron castings that furnish the Baronies' gunsmiths and munitions factories. Lacking the fuel and labor force to operate the refinery full time, the workers cycle through the processes in shifts, locking down one facility to activate another. Pirates and raiders bent on plundering the compound for its valuable resources must direct their attacks on the active facilities, frequently competing with one another for the spoils.

DescriptionText.En: The cities of Nalm and Sylka—siblings locked in rivalry where both border opposite edges of a deadly stretch of barren wasteland. Sands that bind the family together. Rights to scraps littering the dunes, rights to route trade through its airspace. Generations of conflict.

FullDescriptionText.En: The twin oasis cities of Nalm and Sylka have been at war ever since the wandering nomads of the Dunes captured the Nalm oasis and sent its former inhabitants fleeing to Sylka for refuge. For generations, the stretch of sand between them has been a battlefield, as the Sylkans try to reclaim their heritage and the Nalmese try to defend their home.

DescriptionText.En: The hardy settlers of Hanat held their ground for generations, surviving harsh surroundings and perpetual onslaught of pillagers and bandits. They’ve found a new ally to aid in their protection. Can Chaladonian alliances protect the town from the Anglean Raiders?

FullDescriptionText.En: Traders and raiders alike are a frequent sight in the skies over the bergs and sea ice of the Melting Firth, the frigid sea channel that divides Anglea's coast from the Firnfeld mainland. The hardy settlers of Hanat, who have withstood pillage and famine to make this inhospitable stretch of ice their home, welcome the former and live in dread of the latter. When passing ships clash in aerial battles above the fortifications and homesteads of the tiny village, the locals seal themselves tight inside their huts and wait for the storm to pass.

DescriptionText.En: Anglean Raiders roam the Black Channel to hunt down Chaladonian freighters, hoping to steal technology. Fighting spills into the Chattering Fjords. Deadly raiders, research vessels, and vigilant patrols clash amongst the jagged spires. Watery graves await.

FullDescriptionText.En:
Ranging far from their icy island home to the west, Anglean Gatherer ships are raiding coastal settlements up and down both sides of the Black Channel between the Chattering Fjords and the island of Chaladon, striking the towns in blitz attacks to overwhelm their defenses and plunder their food stores.

To counter heightened raider activity in the area, defenders from the Fjord Baronies are increasing patrols in the Teeth, even venturing into Chaladonian territory in order to catch raiders. Near the town of Amida on the coast of Chaladon, a patrol has caught up with a raiding party returning westward with its spoils.

DescriptionText.En: Bent beams, shattered glass—husks of the past. Merchants, scavengers, and raiders alike travel to the ruins to look for what was buried in dust. Perhaps a great technology? More likely the barrel of a gun pointed straight at you, but that never stopped anyone from coming back.

FullDescriptionText.En: Whispers abound that the ruins of the ancient city shadowing humble Paritus conceal untold secrets, lost technologies, and riches free for the taking by any crew bold and enterprising enough to uncover them. The hard truth is that most who come to wander and search among the twisted streets of the Labyrinth find no treasure and little profit for their efforts, save whatever glory can be earned in the frantic and grisly battles that break out whenever opposing seekers meet and clash to determine which has the worthier claim to conduct their plunder. To date nothing of significant value has ever been recovered from the Labyrinth, but it doesn't stop anyone trying.

DescriptionText.En: Veins of the earth carry precious ores.  Split the veins, process the ore, and create death machines to spill more precious resources from veins of our brothers.  The earth weeps and our brethren scream in agony as their vessels fall out of the sky.

FullDescriptionText.En: The Yesha Empire controlled mountain ranges are resource rich.  Many try to sneak away with hauls—a small dip in production for the Yeshan “war machine”—but few make it out alive.  Thus far, the Rusted Mountain Range provide those lucky enough to mine her with bountiful returns.  They say that the range is the womb for our destructive tendencies, supplying us with materials to build devastating weapons.  Chaladonians in the east muse about how the womb supplies nutrients to our airships and that the fighting occurs in the skies puts nutrients back as we kill—blood and metal raining down.  “All is in perfect balance,” they say.  I venture that they are correct.

DescriptionText.En: Every captain has their humble beginnings. Fly, shoot, repair, and spot dummy ships and experiment with different ship loadouts. With a variety of hotkeys at your disposal, you can simulate many combat situations and test your abilities.

FullDescriptionText.En:
— FLY! Get a feel for the wheel and experiment with the helm tools to perform fancy maneuvers.
— SHOOT! Guns are effective against different parts, so practice aiming for the hull, balloon, guns, and engines, and try different ammo and weapons loadouts.
— REPAIR! Test out the different repair and fire-fighting tools when your ship takes damage, and use a buff tool when it's in good shape. Keep hull armor up to protect your core health.
— SPOT! Mark enemy ships with your spyglass (right click to zoom, left click to spot) to keep tabs on them and tell friend from foe.
[TAB] to view teams list; [M] to view local map; set ship priority: [F1] Normal, [F2] Offense, [F3] Defense

DescriptionText.En: There's nothing forgiving about this place.  Devastated by dust storms, and plagued by disease. It makes you wonder what's left? Some don't have the luxury to choose where to live or to migrate to a distant land. There is only perseverance, and it sometimes pays off for the lucky few. I bet we'd outlive the roaches.

DescriptionText.En: Even after contesting the control for Blackcliff Metal Works, there are always reinforcements arriving to put up a final fight.  An already tired day turns to an even longer one as necessary cleanup transpires.  Those who quaffed moonshine in premature celebration are those in for trouble.

Northern territories have been known to hide caches of ancient technology. Buried deep and frozen over by ice, only those with indomitable determination can find them.  Even if something is found, even fewer have the minds to decipher and restore these machines. Who can you whisper and coax the secrets out of these metal souls?

DescriptionText.En: The rocky mountains that run through the western territories have always been a favorite amongst smugglers and those who don't want to be seen. Deep canyons and crevices make for the perfect getaway routes and hiding holes.  Anyone with half a brain knows these routes are best for smuggling, but anyone with the other half knows to avoid these treacherous passes.

DescriptionText.En: Deep beneath the sand, there's evidence that this hell on earth was actually a body of water.  Maybe a great lake, or a splendid sea.  Anything would be better than unrelenting heat that makes everything burn to a crisp.  The blue ocean may have dried up, but the black one lies buried below.  Harvesting the crude oil has attracted many to risk the dangers of this forsaken place.

Over time, the forgotten are reclaimed by the earth. If one acts quickly enough, remains can be salvaged from the grips of nonexistence. After cutting into the ground, deep gashes are left behind and its treasures hauled out.  No matter how much digging, riches are still unearthed. Excavations across the desert all look the same. Even the sand cannot outpace the shoveling to heal the scars and pockmarks that mark the earth.

DescriptionText.En: For the lucky few that manage to get their boots on a proper airship, the first thing they learn is how to keep the vessel in the sky. Engineer training is crucial for everyone, because every fantasy about being an airman is contingent on the ship not plummeting to the ground.

FullDescriptionText.En: Learn to be a good Engineer, and do other stuff good too.

DescriptionText.En: After keeping the airship aloft, the next most important thing for a crewman to know is how to use it's armaments. But gunning is a little more complicated on these ship than just pointing and pulling the trigger.

FullDescriptionText.En: Learn to be a good Gunner, and do other stuff good too.

DescriptionText.En: Arguably the most important role, Pilots have the responsibility of getting the airship where it needs to go and getting it's guns lined up. More often than not they also direct the crew of their ship, and it's their leadership which can determine victory or defeat.

FullDescriptionText.En: Introduction to the Pilot Class.

DescriptionText.En: Tutorial for Alliance

FullDescriptionText.En: Tutorial for Alliance

DescriptionText.En: Many attempt to use the dense fogs and towering rock outcroppings to hide their getaway between the Black Channel and Chattering Fjords close to the Chaladon coastline.  However, the same perceived advantages can also pose as significant threats to one's escape.

The ruined cities may be a scenic detour for some, but for others it is a refuge.  The impossibly tall buildings and narrow avenues make it great for clandestine meetings and getaway. Maybe there's a chance for the city to be crowded again.

DescriptionText.En: There's nothing forgiving about this place. Devastated by dust storms, and plagued by disease. It makes you wonder what's left? Some don't have the luxury to choose where to live or to migrate to a distant land. There is only perseverance, and it sometimes pays off for the lucky few. I bet we'd outlive the roaches.

They the narrows are haunted.  The streams used to run clear but now they are red.  Red with what?  If you're so inclined to believe a spooky tale then its red with those who died from the accidents that were common in the refineries.  It's unclear why there were so many mishaps, but it's clear that something doesn't want outsiders from staying too long.

The cities of Nalm and Sylka—siblings locked in rivalry where both border opposite edges of a deadly stretch of barren wasteland. Sands that bind the family together. Rights to scraps littering the dunes, rights to route trade through its airspace. Generations of conflict.

FullDescriptionText.En: The twin oasis cities of Nalm and Sylka have been at war ever since the wandering nomads of the Dunes captured the Nalm oasis and sent its former inhabitants fleeing to Sylka for refuge. For generations, the stretch of sand between them has been a battlefield, as the Sylkans try to reclaim their heritage and the Nalmese try to defend their home.

DescriptionText.En: All kinds of dignitaries travel back and forth through Glowwater Bay.  Many are Baronite lords and ladies while others are unknown and on more secretive missions. Who knows who you might find. Cautious caravans cruelly caught.

Violent winds are just a part of life in the desert. Sand is swept into the air and clogs any engine that may find its sorry way through the storm. Can you blame the navigator for this unforeseen force of nature? Is being thrown overboard a yes?

How many battles has Hanat seen recently? The sound of airships exploding is their morning call like the cock's crow everywhere else in the world. One more fleet hunting its prey won't make a difference. At least the skies are alight with daily fireworks.

DescriptionText.En: Anglean Raiders roam the Black Channel to hunt down Chaladonian freighters, hoping to steal technology. Fighting spills into the Chattering Fjords. Deadly raiders, research vessels, and vigilant patrols clash amongst the jagged spires. Watery graves await.

FullDescriptionText.En:
Ranging far from their icy island home to the west, Anglean Gatherer ships are raiding coastal settlements up and down both sides of the Black Channel between the Chattering Fjords and the island of Chaladon, striking the towns in blitz attacks to overwhelm their defenses and plunder their food stores.

To counter heightened raider activity in the area, defenders from the Fjord Baronies are increasing patrols in the Teeth, even venturing into Chaladonian territory in order to catch raiders. Near the town of Amida on the coast of Chaladon, a patrol has caught up with a raiding party returning westward with its spoils.

DescriptionText.En: Some disputes are not about survival. Some are just a show of might. The Dust brought fierce winds Combined with the obelisk-like ribs of old vessels of destruction, battles fought in this edge of the desert are only for those with cunning... or nothing to lose.

FullDescriptionText.En: Some scores can only be settled in combat. Choose a second and meet your foes on the field of battle to duke it out once and for all. May the best team win.

DescriptionText.En: Merchants look at two things when deciding on a route: distance and chance of an ambush.  While the Red Canyon is the shortest distance between the Yesha Empire and Anglean Republic, it is also littered with chasms and gullies—happy hunting, safe travels!

FullDescriptionText.En: A favored trade route for merchants making the run north from the Yesha Empire up to Cusichaca on the coast, the Red Canyons are also a prime spot for ambush, and many an unwary captain has been waylaid with a hold full of goods among the red rocks and ruins in this desolate stretch of chasms and gullies. The Canyons also offer the shortest flight path between the Empire and the Republic, although the region's hardscrabble hamlets are slim pickings and Anglean Gatherers out on a raiding mission can find easier targets than the well-defended cities of the Yesha heartland.

DescriptionText.En: King Greger’s influence, of the Fjord Baronies, is weak in this icy stretch north of Glowwater Bay. While an important foothold in Firnfeld, the area is rife with pirates and marauders that often come into contact with patrol ship from the Baronites. Cold cloudy combat climbs.

FullDescriptionText.En: North of Glowwater Bay, the Chattering Fjords seasonal melt gives way to permafrost and a coast cluttered year-round with ice. The Fjord Baronies extended its territory north into this beautiful but forbidding land with the siege and capture of the Navinstaak military base almost thirty years ago, gaining a foothold in icebound Firnfeld and a new remote holding to secure. King Greger's influence is weakly felt this far from the Kingseat, and though patrols from Glowwater and Northlake make their rounds through the territory, in truth this icy stretch of coast is rife with bandits and pirates ready to tussle with any unwary explorer or insufficiently armed patrol ship, and conflicts are common in the region.

DescriptionText.En: The hardy settlers of Hanat held their ground for generations, surviving harsh surroundings and perpetual onslaught of pillagers and bandits. They’ve found a new ally to aid in their protection. Can Chaladonian alliances protect the town from the Anglean Raiders?

FullDescriptionText.En: Traders and raiders alike are a frequent sight in the skies over the bergs and sea ice of the Melting Firth, the frigid sea channel that divides Anglea's coast from the Firnfeld mainland. The hardy settlers of Hanat, who have withstood pillage and famine to make this inhospitable stretch of ice their home, welcome the former and live in dread of the latter. When passing ships clash in aerial battles above the fortifications and homesteads of the tiny village, the locals seal themselves tight inside their huts and wait for the storm to pass.

DescriptionText.En: Bent beams, shattered glass—husks of the past. Merchants, scavengers, and raiders alike travel to the ruins to look for what was buried in dust. Perhaps a great technology? More likely the barrel of a gun pointed straight at you, but that never stopped anyone from coming back.

FullDescriptionText.En: Whispers abound that the ruins of the ancient city shadowing humble Paritus conceal untold secrets, lost technologies, and riches free for the taking by any crew bold and enterprising enough to uncover them. The hard truth is that most who come to wander and search among the twisted streets of the Labyrinth find no treasure and little profit for their efforts, save whatever glory can be earned in the frantic and grisly battles that break out whenever opposing seekers meet and clash to determine which has the worthier claim to conduct their plunder. To date nothing of significant value has ever been recovered from the Labyrinth, but it doesn't stop anyone trying.

Northern territories have been known to hide caches of ancient technology. Buried deep and frozen over by ice, only those with indomitable determination can find them.  Even if something is found, even fewer have the minds to decipher and restore these machines. Who can you whisper and coax the secrets out of these metal souls?

DescriptionText.En: Those in Anglea live in austerity, wedged into frozen skyscrapers and husks of military bases. Their surroundings, though, are rich in old technology, attracting raiders to the poor town of Hanat. The tundra in disarray, none to keep raiders at bay.

FullDescriptionText.En:
With its frozen cities wedged in the skeletons of ancient skyscrapers and the husks of old military bases, the Anglean Republic is rich in technological remains, but resource-poor. Valiant Gatherer crews set out in search of resources and food to feed the hungry mouths back home, oftentimes plundering from the storehouses of unfortunate villages in the path of their raiding fleets.

Always vigilant, Hanat has a network of sentry towers to alert the villagers of approaching raiders and assemble allies to its defense. One of those allies is the Order of Chaladon, which in the interests of peace has pledged ships to repel unprovoked attacks on the town.

DescriptionText.En: Lutessa seems like an idyllic land on the southern tip of the Isles of Chaladon. The water is clear, and green fills the eye. On closer inspection, though, scars of the past reveal themselves readily. Recently, when a dam of the old world was repaired, further wounds were shown in the landscape. Massive bunkers hinted at mighty battles that happened in the past. Though these guns are no longer functional, the skies above often thunder with the sound of new strife, and the threat of new scars. The skies hold new danger.

The rocky mountains that run through the western territories have always been a favorite amongst smugglers and those who don't want to be seen. Deep canyons and crevices make for the perfect getaway routes and hiding holes. Anyone with half a brain knows these routes are best for smuggling, but anyone with the other half knows to avoid these treacherous passes.

DescriptionText.En: The land is unpredictable. On some days, villages are swallowed whole by floods. On others, mountains shear creating daunting cliff faces into nothingness. Occasionally, the changes reveal secrets and hidden treasure, but who knows when the earth will swallow it all again.

DescriptionText.En: Northern territories have been known to hide caches of ancient technology. Buried deep and frozen over by ice, only those with indomitable determination can find them. Even if something is found, even fewer have the minds to decipher and restore these machines. Who can you whisper and coax the secrets out of these metal souls?

Every captain has their humble beginnings. Fly, shoot, repair, and spot dummy ships and experiment with different ship loadouts. With a variety of hotkeys at your disposal, you can simulate many combat situations and test your abilities.

FullDescriptionText.En:
— FLY! Get a feel for the wheel and experiment with the helm tools to perform fancy maneuvers.
— SHOOT! Guns are effective against different parts, so practice aiming for the hull, balloon, guns, and engines, and try different ammo and weapons loadouts.
— REPAIR! Test out the different repair and fire-fighting tools when your ship takes damage, and use a buff tool when it's in good shape. Keep hull armor up to protect your core health.
— SPOT! Mark enemy ships with your spyglass (right click to zoom, left click to spot) to keep tabs on them and tell friend from foe.
[TAB] to view teams list; [M] to view local map; set ship priority: [F1] Normal, [F2] Offense, [F3] Defense

DescriptionText.En: Beyond treacherous lava fields, in the northern edge of the Ash Mountain range, lie Yeshan strongholds of Yao Ling Pass. Previously inaccessible, air travel has allowed the snowy cliffs and wandering ridges to prosper. Though not as active as the central Ash Mountains, volcanic steam clouds blanket the industrial area. The warmth trapped the mountains fuel the power of the Yeshan war machine.

An already tired day turns to an even longer one as necessary cleanup transpires. Those who quaffed moonshine in premature celebration are those in for trouble.

Deep beneath the sand, there's evidence that this hell on earth was actually a body of water. Maybe a great lake, or a splendid sea. Anything would be better than unrelenting heat that makes everything burn to a crisp. The blue ocean may have dried up, but the black one lies buried below. Harvesting the crude oil has attracted many to risk the dangers of this forsaken place.

The cities of Nalm and Sylka—siblings locked in rivalry where both border opposite edges of a deadly stretch of barren wasteland. Sands that bind the family together. Rights to scraps littering the dunes, rights to route trade through its airspace. Generations of conflict.

FullDescriptionText.En: The twin oasis cities of Nalm and Sylka have been at war ever since the wandering nomads of the Dunes captured the Nalm oasis and sent its former inhabitants fleeing to Sylka for refuge. For generations, the stretch of sand between them has been a battlefield, as the Sylkans try to reclaim their heritage and the Nalmese try to defend their home.

DescriptionText.En: Anglean Raiders roam the Black Channel to hunt down Chaladonian freighters, hoping to steal technology. Fighting spills into the Chattering Fjords. Deadly raiders, research vessels, and vigilant patrols clash amongst the jagged spires. Watery graves await.

FullDescriptionText.En:
Ranging far from their icy island home to the west, Anglean Gatherer ships are raiding coastal settlements up and down both sides of the Black Channel between the Chattering Fjords and the island of Chaladon, striking the towns in blitz attacks to overwhelm their defenses and plunder their food stores.

To counter heightened raider activity in the area, defenders from the Fjord Baronies are increasing patrols in the Teeth, even venturing into Chaladonian territory in order to catch raiders. Near the town of Amida on the coast of Chaladon, a patrol has caught up with a raiding party returning westward with its spoils.

DescriptionText.En: Some disputes are not about survival. Some are just a show of might. The Dust brought fierce winds Combined with the obelisk-like ribs of old vessels of destruction, battles fought in this edge of the desert are only for those with cunning... or nothing to lose.

FullDescriptionText.En: Some scores can only be settled in combat. Choose a second and meet your foes on the field of battle to duke it out once and for all. May the best team win.

DescriptionText.En: Merchants look at two things when deciding on a route: distance and chance of an ambush.  While the Red Canyon is the shortest distance between the Yesha Empire and Anglean Republic, it is also littered with chasms and gullies—happy hunting, safe travels!

FullDescriptionText.En: A favored trade route for merchants making the run north from the Yesha Empire up to Cusichaca on the coast, the Red Canyons are also a prime spot for ambush, and many an unwary captain has been waylaid with a hold full of goods among the red rocks and ruins in this desolate stretch of chasms and gullies. The Canyons also offer the shortest flight path between the Empire and the Republic, although the region's hardscrabble hamlets are slim pickings and Anglean Gatherers out on a raiding mission can find easier targets than the well-defended cities of the Yesha heartland.

DescriptionText.En: aKing Greger’s influence, of the Fjord Baronies, is weak in this icy stretch north of Glowwater Bay. While an important foothold in Firnfeld, the area is rife with pirates and marauders that often come into contact with patrol ship from the Baronites. Cold cloudy combat climbs.

FullDescriptionText.En: North of Glowwater Bay, the Chattering Fjords seasonal melt gives way to permafrost and a coast cluttered year-round with ice. The Fjord Baronies extended its territory north into this beautiful but forbidding land with the siege and capture of the Navinstaak military base almost thirty years ago, gaining a foothold in icebound Firnfeld and a new remote holding to secure. King Greger's influence is weakly felt this far from the Kingseat, and though patrols from Glowwater and Northlake make their rounds through the territory, in truth this icy stretch of coast is rife with bandits and pirates ready to tussle with any unwary explorer or insufficiently armed patrol ship, and conflicts are common in the region.

DescriptionText.En: Bent beams, shattered glass—husks of the past. Merchants, scavengers, and raiders alike travel to the ruins to look for what was buried in dust. Perhaps a great technology? More likely the barrel of a gun pointed straight at you, but that never stopped anyone from coming back.

FullDescriptionText.En: Whispers abound that the ruins of the ancient city shadowing humble Paritus conceal untold secrets, lost technologies, and riches free for the taking by any crew bold and enterprising enough to uncover them. The hard truth is that most who come to wander and search among the twisted streets of the Labyrinth find no treasure and little profit for their efforts, save whatever glory can be earned in the frantic and grisly battles that break out whenever opposing seekers meet and clash to determine which has the worthier claim to conduct their plunder. To date nothing of significant value has ever been recovered from the Labyrinth, but it doesn't stop anyone trying.

DescriptionText.En: The hardy settlers of Hanat held their ground for generations, surviving harsh surroundings and perpetual onslaught of pillagers and bandits. They’ve found a new ally to aid in their protection. Can Chaladonian alliances protect the town from the Anglean Raiders?

FullDescriptionText.En: aTraders and raiders alike are a frequent sight in the skies over the bergs and sea ice of the Melting Firth, the frigid sea channel that divides Anglea's coast from the Firnfeld mainland. The hardy settlers of Hanat, who have withstood pillage and famine to make this inhospitable stretch of ice their home, welcome the former and live in dread of the latter. When passing ships clash in aerial battles above the fortifications and homesteads of the tiny village, the locals seal themselves tight inside their huts and wait for the storm to pass.

The Fjord Baronies control many industrial assets, including the Blackcliff Metal Works. Baronites must be vigilant while transporting their labor forces from factory to factory because brigands wait for the chance to plunder their rich ore and steel.

FullDescriptionText.En: The Blackcliff Metal Works are one of the Fjords' key industrial assets, processing the iron ores mined in the Eastern Ridge into the steel and iron castings that furnish the Baronies' gunsmiths and munitions factories. Lacking the fuel and labor force to operate the refinery full time, the workers cycle through the processes in shifts, locking down one facility to activate another. Pirates and raiders bent on plundering the compound for its valuable resources must direct their attacks on the active facilities, frequently competing with one another for the spoils.

DescriptionText.En: The Flayed Hills harbor immense wealth and fortune for those brave enough to mine in disputed territory bordering the Yeshan Empire.  Buried oil caches, forgotten wartime munitions, collapsed mines. Can you outrun the Yeshans with hulls brimming with cargo?

FullDescriptionText.En: Lying just outside the territory controlled by the Yesha Empire, the contested Flayed Hills badlands hide considerable wealth beneath their barren surface. Collapsed mines conceal seams of iron and even buried oil caches, forgotten stockpiles of an ancient military. Even more valuable are the abandoned wells tapping deep underground aquifers.  Clean drinking water is scarce in the Rusted Range mountains, and the Empire needs to look beyond its borders to supply its growing cities. Cutting out the Yesha merchant middlemen, the towns of the Arashi League are mounting expeditions to collect water and other resources straight from the source and carry them home to the parched and dusty Arashi Desert.

DescriptionText.En: Those in Anglea live in austerity, wedged into frozen skyscrapers and husks of military bases. Their surroundings, though, are rich in old technology, attracting raiders to the poor town of Hanat. The tundra in disarray, none to keep raiders at bay.

FullDescriptionText.En:
With its frozen cities wedged in the skeletons of ancient skyscrapers and the husks of old military bases, the Anglean Republic is rich in technological remains, but resource-poor. Valiant Gatherer crews set out in search of resources and food to feed the hungry mouths back home, oftentimes plundering from the storehouses of unfortunate villages in the path of their raiding fleets.

Always vigilant, Hanat has a network of sentry towers to alert the villagers of approaching raiders and assemble allies to its defense. One of those allies is the Order of Chaladon, which in the interests of peace has pledged ships to repel unprovoked attacks on the town.

Unable to penetrate the walled city of Anvala, attackers shift their attention to the Crown Mountain range that house industrial complexes used by the city. However, privateers always arrive at the sound of coins clinking in a bag, and Anvala has plenty of it, even if it means going up against explosive laden convoys. So long as the price is right!

What flows through the massive pipes twisting through coastline of the Vastness? A Merchant would pretend not to hear. Ask again, and he’ll tell your friends that you wandered off. Still, that doesn’t stop raiders from crossing the Abyssal Gulf to try their luck leaching the pipes dry of whatever flows within. A risky endeavor where many seemed to have wandered off.

Over hundreds of years, river rapids carved out beautiful and treacherous canyons into the base of the Forest Ridge Mountains. The rivers are long gone, but they exposed valuable mineral deposits. Most would think it a fool's errand to work this particular land, but with enough time and desperation anything is possible. Maybe someday, we'll see the fish swim through these streams again.

The Oblivion River holds a great enigma of the past: a black ship of unimaginable scale.It may even be larger than those consumed by The Wastes. Due to its dilapidation, its function is uncertain. Did it travel on the air, the sea, or even under the waves? Maybe by land? Further study is difficult, though, as the ruins hide as many enemies as it does secrets.

Did it travel on the air, the sea, or even under the waves? Maybe by land? Further study is difficult, though, as the ruins hide as many enemies as it does secrets.

There’s always ruckus near the Oblivion River. Excavation sites spring up like weeds. Rumors speak of a lost artifact with the destructive power of the black leviathan. Or it could just be a cache of gold, which is still good. Whatever it may be, scavengers are quick to move during any lulls in battle. Fortune and destruction tend to lead to the same result.

Further study is difficult, though, as the ruins hide as many enemies as it does secrets.

High in the Ridge Forest Mountains on the border of Aspara and Skyend resides a vast complex of uninhabited buildings. The crumbling buildings are plain on the outside, but adorned with what seems to be ornate religious carvings on the interior. Despite the age of the structures, there are many functional sky docks upon the rooftops. Until recently, the Fjord Baronites had kept this temple hidden from the outside world. An Anglean invasion stumbled upon the complex after cutting the Baronite territory in half. It is unknown what the Baronites were protecting here, but invaders and treasure hunters aim to find out. Outposts and mining rigs spring up like forests. Will their answers be found, or will they all be reduced to rubble?

DescriptionText.En: On a remote section of the Crown Mountain Range, privateers have found a prime spot to salvage ore and oil spilled out of the mighty machinery of Anvala. A rich haul can be made with a sturdy ship and steadfast crew. The skies are often filled with other crews with the same idea, and no intention of sharing. Are you willing to take the gambit for a few more coins in your pocket?

FullDescriptionText.En: A massive glacier marks the entrance to the Anglean capital of Kinforth. Almost nothing is known about what lies beyond the glacier, as trespass is met with instant and deadly force. The ruins of the ancient city at the base of the glacier are of little concern to the Angleans, however, having been picked clean of technology long ago. Squabbles between pirates on their doorstep are most often left to themselves, with crews emerging to salvage the aftermath. In a show of dark humor, the crews have been known to build massive snowmen to observe the battles from hidden places around the broken city.

DescriptionText.En: Crown Brawl

Every captain has their humble beginnings. Fly, shoot, repair, and spot dummy ships and experiment with different ship loadouts. With a variety of hotkeys at your disposal, you can simulate many combat situations and test your abilities.

FullDescriptionText.En:
— FLY! Get a feel for the wheel and experiment with the helm tools to perform fancy maneuvers.
— SHOOT! Guns are effective against different parts, so practice aiming for the hull, balloon, guns, and engines, and try different ammo and weapons loadouts.
— REPAIR! Test out the different repair and fire-fighting tools when your ship takes damage, and use a buff tool when it's in good shape. Keep hull armor up to protect your core health.
— SPOT! Mark enemy ships with your spyglass (right click to zoom, left click to spot) to keep tabs on them and tell friend from foe.
[TAB] to view teams list; [M] to view local map; set ship priority: [F1] Normal, [F2] Offense, [F3] Defense

DescriptionText.En: A massive glacier marks the entrance to the Anglean capital of Kinforth. Almost nothing is known about what lies beyond the glacier, as trespass is met with instant and deadly force. The ruins of the ancient city at the base of the glacier are of little concern to the Angleans, however, having been picked clean of technology long ago. Squabbles between pirates on their doorstep are most often left to themselves, with crews emerging to salvage the aftermath. In a show of dark humor, the crews have been known to build large snowmen to observe the battles from hidden places around the broken city.

Lutessa seems like an idyllic land on the southern tip of the Isles of Chaladon. The water is clear, and green fills the eye. On closer inspection, though, scars of the past reveal themselves readily. Recently, when a dam of the old world was repaired, further wounds were shown in the landscape. Massive bunkers hinted at mighty battles that happened in the past. Though these guns are no longer functional, the skies above often thunder with the sound of new strife, and the threat of new scars. The skies hold new danger.

Some disputes are not about survival. Some are just a show of might. The Dust brought fierce winds Combined with the obelisk-like ribs of old vessels of destruction, battles fought in this edge of the desert are only for those with cunning... or nothing to lose.

FullDescriptionText.En: Some scores can only be settled in combat. Choose a second and meet your foes on the field of battle to duke it out once and for all. May the best team win.

DescriptionText.En: Sand, bluffs, and peril await those that trespass in the skies of the Arashi.
Some say this is the cradle of the new age of air, if legends are true.
The beauty of the isles belays the dangerous teeth hidden just below the surface.
Even paradise can succumb to the darkness of war.
The frigid north welcomes no one with its deathly chill embrace.
Sometimes the most unremarkable places become the stage to enact the most influential moments in history.
When traveling the fjords, one must wonder if the chill felt is born of the inclement weather, or the eyes of death watching from the ice.
Only a fool would think to travel the entire untamed badlands stretching from the Arashi Desert to the Anglean Sea of Graves.
This poisoned land spews forth the most toxic of dangers. Be wary the foot that treads here.
Bitter battles are fought to this day over bones of the old world buried in the sands of the Wastes. More than a few brave, or perhaps foolhardy, souls have added their own bones to these relics.
Char and ash leave a bitter taste on the tongue. This has little comparison with the bitterness of the battles that one partakes in over these desolate lands of molten rock and fire.

The Isles of Chaladon are a green jewel in the sands and dust of the war torn lands. As with any jewel, this makes it of great value. This often leads to strife for those that do not possess such lands of their own.

Occupying a large swath of Aspara and extending into Lookout, Sunder, and Bannen's Rest, the Ridge Forest and mountain range of the same name are equally wild and rough. There are rumors of pirates in the crags of the tall mountains and tree-filled valleys. The weather is often harsh and unpredictable. Often times, ships that enter never return, or sometimes drift back out, devoid of crew. Superstitious men whisper of voices being heard on any wind that passes the peaks. Be it rumors of pirates, or the untamed weather, normal trade ships avoid this area, lest they be added to the growing list of missing ships and crews.
The frozen Island of Anglea is home to the Anglean Republic. Little is known about the inter workings of the cities hidden in the Anglean snow and ice.
Applies towards Muse items only. Can not be used with Workshop items.
Launches a single explosive rocket over medium/long range.
A smaller Flak Cannon, this gun fires explosive rounds over a medium to long range with a high rate of fire.  Arming time of 0.5 seconds, no AoE Burst damage under 200m.
A close-range piercing weapon with a very high rate of fire, singularly effective against armor.
Unleash all hell on an enemy ship at close range with a jet of fire.

NameText.En: Typhon Heavy Flak Cannon Mk. I

DescriptionText.En: A medium/long-range cannon that fires explosive projectiles dealing substantial damage with a wide area of effect. Arming time of 2/3s, no secondary AoE under 200m.
Fires a wide shotgun burst of shredding projectiles at close range.
Will attach to hulls and reel enemies in when secondary fire button is held.
Fires a brightly burning flare that hovers in the air to reveal ships hidden in cloud cover. Can also be used as a weapon to cause fire damage.  Arming time of 0.6667s.
A slow-firing, long-range scoped cannon that fires powerful explosive rounds.

Fires a blinding barrage of 20 rockets for a powerful area-of-denial effect in close to mid range engagements. While devastating up close, this gun quickly loses effectiveness due to a high missile spread and jaw rattling gun recoil. 

Missiles will start detonating at 750 meters due to crude and inaccurate timer fuses. Detonations will continue for approximately 1 more second with a few missiles reaching targets 1060 meters away. Don't let this range fool you, as this beast can't barely hit the broad side of a Galleon at those ranges. Best to hold your shots and wait for the buggers to get closer. - Wilson
Capable of firing heavy explosive shells over short/medium range, but with limited accuracy.
Rapidly fires a stream of explosive rockets that have a chance to light components on fire.
Shoots a column of fire to engulf ships at close engagement range.
Fires a harpoon that can snare and tether another ship.
A larger, slower, more powerful Carronade that fires a piercing short-range shotgun burst. Effective against balloons and components.

Every captain has their humble beginnings. Fly, shoot, repair, and spot dummy ships and experiment with different ship loadouts. With a variety of hotkeys at your disposal, you can simulate many combat situations and test your abilities.
A rusted and nigh-useless weapon.

High arcing weapon with balloon damaging Flechette AoE. Arming time of 0.727s, Guns with arming time do not inflict the second listed damage before arming. No AoE damage under 200m.

High parabolic arc, narrow range of motion, and slow projectile velocity make this a difficult gun to master, requiring high skill and experience.
Seasonal item
Seasonal item

She cares for the wounded and the sick, the poor, brave souls broken on the battlefield.  Her compassion and her resolve to fight suffering wherever it rears its vicious head make her beloved across the land.

Though his visage may be unsettling, it masks a heart full of kindness and empathy for the ailing and injured.  The good doctor fashioned this special respirator to protect himself as he practices medicine above the clouds.
Seasonal item
Seasonal item

Many years ago a lone pilot flew his ship, the Icarus, in a valiant last battle against marauding pirates. His bravery and self-sacrifice live on in tales told across the land. Exclusive for players of Flight of Icarus.

Many years ago a lone pilot flew his ship, the Icarus, in a valiant last battle against marauding pirates. His bravery and self-sacrifice live on in tales told across the land. Exclusive for players of Flight of Icarus.
Lays proximity-detonated floating mines at short range. Mines will arm and deploy after 3 seconds. Each gun supports 5 mines at a time; extras will self-destruct.

A mid to long-range armor melting weapon with arcing shots. A higher skilled gun that can be terrifying in the right hands. Arming time of 0.6s, no AoE under 150m with default ammo. Ammo types that will reduce arming range list either reduced velocity or reduced arming time.
A proven capacity not to confuse various spinning cogs with the steering wheel.
No longer needs notes stuck on the helm for port and aft.
Can keep control of the ship and my stomach during intense maneuvers.
Knows how much moonshine the engines and my liver can handle.
Through trial and a lot of error, have figured out what all the buttons, switches, and levers do.
Has found a suitable pair of glasses to look heroic in.
"From the wreckage of other ships, we will set our path with our simple motto, 'Not that way."
"Once I break through the storm clouds, it's as bright as a summer day."
More at home in the clouds than on the ground.
"My paper airplanes have traveled further than most warships."
"I know the limits of every ship and how to exceed them."
Rarely has to use the Chain of Command during disciplinary beatings.
"Heroic Last stands are too easy, I specialize in surviving and winning no matter the odds."
"A good commander wins the charge, a great commander wins the war."
"I would say let's make this a fair fight, but there aren't enough ships in your fleet."
Recently stopped trying to throw bullets at enemy ships.
Not completely trusted with anything more dangerous than a slingshot.
Understands the basics: "Bullet goes into the other ship."
Subscribe to the "Spray and Pray" method of attack.
"I used to bulls-eye pigeons back home, your crew will be easy targets."
"Dip, Duck, Dodge, Die!"
The louder the boom, the bigger the fun.
"My dust and sparks shall undo steel."
Our first shot will be this battle's last.
The rumble of thunder instills less fear than the sound of my weapon being loaded.
"Ever see a speck on the horizon burst into flames?"
"Keep running, you'll only die tired."
Has been known to destroy ships with nothing but a stern glance.
Play the weapon like a fine instrument with destruction as music.
Inhale Gunpowder and breathe fire.
More at home with a mop than a spanner.
Have learned not to refer to the top of the wrench as "the whacky end."
"If it's still moving, I don't count it as broken."
Not replaceable by a relatively untrained monkey.
Once fixed the ships phonograph with a single good smack.
Some promotions come from merit, some from vacancy and accidental fires.
"You see this part right here?  This shouldn't have been removed."
"I've made a special modification. All the engines will now go up to 11."
Can fix a compressor in under a minute while it's on fire.
"Give me a 12 volt bulb and rubber band and I'll be able to rebuild your engine."
"The ship's manual calls for 1,500 bolts, I bet I can put her together with half that."
Has installed all the additional features: stabilizers, heated seats, cup holders.
My patch jobs have been more thorough than many others' best works.
Can build a ship from scratch using only parts found in the kitchen.
As long as a few scraps remain, there is no such thing as broken.
"I'd be happy to say some kind words over his grave." - Receive 20 commendations, Receive 10 commendations from players level 4+
"No matter the outcome of this battle, it has been an honor." - Receive 30 commendations, Receive 10 commendations from captains
"Your crew will be well taken care of. Know that I hold no ill will towards you." - Receive 40 commendations, Receive 10 commendations from enemy captains

"I'm going to give you the same advice my old teacher gave me. 'Don't get me killed on this one,' God rest his soul." - Receive 20 commendations from players level 1-3, Play 30 matches with all crewmates level 1-3

"The best advice I can give is to find someone who's still alive and follow them. Chances are their body will block the first shot." - Receive 30 commendations from players level 1-3, Receive 10 commendations from captains level 1-3
"A graduating class of three is three more than I expected to survive." - Receive 40 commendations from players level 1-3, Play 30 matches with all crewmates level 1-3
"Even when bullets are flying and ships are crashing, I am here to help." - A community volunteer with a proven record for helping the community.
"I have walked along the broken earth." - Those who have taken part in the uncompleted parts of the game and helped us test it.
"We all have dreams, I make them reality." - Backed us on Kickstarter and made Guns of Icarus a reality!

Humans are always going to make war, and when they do, they're going to require arms. That's where you come in. They may call you a Merchant of Death, but woe betide anyone who comes after your ship, for you have weapons enough to equip a small army.
Her compassionate face watches over you as you fly, granting you luck and fair weather on your journeys through the skies.

It doesn't matter if you aren't actually part of the royal family--nobility is a state of mind. Flying an opulent ship decked out in gold leaf and purple velvet, you comport yourself with the grace and poise of a palace-born blue-blood.
Rallying the earth-bound under the banner of the righteous, your ship is an avenging angel smiting evil from on high, brilliant as the clarion call of a trumpet from the heavens.
With scales of iron and eyes of fire, your beast soars above, terrible to look upon, "chiefest and greatest of Calamities."

Sunlight flashes off their golden backs as the fish circle lazily in the cool water, unhurried and at peace with the world. What better image to evoke the confident flight of your airship as you roam under the noon day sun?
This mythical creature is known for its strength and ferocity. It is said that this king of beasts acts as a powerful guardian, making it an excellent choice for a brave captain's emblem.
You have incurred my wrath! Prepare to writhe in agony as I wreak my horrific revenge!

Have you ever heard the howl of a wolf at night? On cold nights the pack members lift their muzzles to the moon and sing their primal song. From your bed you hear and realize that outside your flimsy walls is the cruel vastness of the forest, and that you are just a weak little animal, alone in the world. That's the fear your ship strikes into the hearts of your enemies.

One must respect this clever cephalopod, for it is able to use its eight agile arms to slip out of even the tightest of jams. Perhaps such a creature will serve well as a symbol of your ship, keeping you safe in battle.
A bird of prey with claws outstretched to adorn the prow of your ship, proclaiming you the apex predator of the skies.

You can keep your fancy bric-a-brac, your extraneous gilt and glamour, we prefer the stream-lined aesthetics of the machine. We are the true spirit of Industry: the makers, the inventors, the steam-powered work-horses who keep your clock-work world running on time.

You have traveled to the far reaches of the known world, and everywhere you have gone you have found fascinating things with which to fill your hold. Delicate artifacts, plush carpets, trinkets and charms fashioned by the skillful hands of foreign artisans, your ship is a treasure trove of the rare and beautiful.

A well-rounded, balanced ship with average durability and firepower.

FullDescriptionText.En: The Goldfish is one of the earliest airships still in production and use today. First manufactured in the independent midland territories before their collapse, it is often seen as the basis for other ship designs. With a powerful fore-mounted weapon and multiple side weapon slots, it requires some skill and maneuvering to utilize the full potential of this ship.best used as a flanking and ambush ship. Weaker builds include Flak and Minotaur as front guns. Stronger builds are Hwacha and Carronade.

DescriptionText.En: A medium-sized fighter with a large complement of small weapons.

FullDescriptionText.En: From an Arashi blueprint for building an airworthy ship with a minimum of materials, this spare, skeletal ship has found favor with mercenaries and freelancers who make their living from salvage, trade, and other odd jobs. Though its improvised scrap-metal construction is not the sturdiest, the Junker is very well armed and relies on its weapon-studded gun deck and nimble ship turning to help ward off trouble. While the Junker has a thin hull profile, its main weakness is its large balloon, which is a prime target for Flechette and fire attacks.

DescriptionText.En: A small, fast, lightly armed scout with an asymmetrical deck layout.

FullDescriptionText.En: A catamaran originally of Chaladonian design, the delicate Squid cuts a distinctive figure with its split deck, off-center helm, and tripartite hull. Prized for its speed and maneuverability, the Squid is popular as an assault and raiding vessel. In battle, the nimble Squid can gain a positional advantage and protect its unarmed port-side flank by outmaneuvering heavier, slower ships.

DescriptionText.En: A large, slow, durable warship with multiple decks and heavily armed broadside flanks.

FullDescriptionText.En: A sturdily-built warship with an imposing vertical silhouette, the Galleon was introduced by Yesha shipbuilders as a sentinel to patrol the borders of the Empire and keep the peace. With its isolated aftcastle helm and multiple lower decks, the Galleon requires a large, coordinated crew to operate. Though the weighty, bulky hull limits its mobility, the Galleon asserts its authority with powerful arrays of medium weapons that spell doom for opponents caught in range of its deadly broadsides.

DescriptionText.En: A vertical spiral-shaped ship with four stacked decks and high turning speed.

FullDescriptionText.En: The towering Spire is a sentry ship originally built to guard the mountain passes of the Fjordlanders. The earliest models were nearly stationary, with weak thruster engines and a weapon pointed in every cardinal direction to cover all approaches. When decommissioned Spires were later modified for use in battle fleets, the rear gun was moved to concentrate fire forward. While their forward speed is limited, they can rotate easily around their center to bring their guns to bear and protect their exposed stern.

DescriptionText.En: A powerful front-line charger with twin forward guns, an armor-plated beak, and limited maneuverability.

FullDescriptionText.En: The Pyramidion is a modified version of a Yesha warship used in the vanguard of an offensive fleet formation, often backed by a line of smaller striker craft. With its narrow head-on profile and armor-plated balloon, it is a front-line charger of the first order, able to soften a target with concentrated fire from its twin forward guns before ramming for the kill with its reinforced beak. Despite its wide turn radius, it is prized for its overall durability and ability to concentrate fire.

DescriptionText.En: Get into the action quickly!

FullDescriptionText.En: OH MAN HURRY QUICK GET IN THE GAME, YO

DescriptionText.En: An unconventional forward-armed attack skimmer with a subducted balloon and exposed weather deck.

FullDescriptionText.En: Legend has it that the first Mobula was constructed by Vastness shipwrights for a princess or wealthy merchant who demanded a pleasure barge from which she might enjoy an unobstructed view of the night sky, though most assume that is just a sales pitch. Aside from legends, they are one of the first ships mass produced in Mercantile Guild lands, often used as sentinels and city guards due to their slow speed and plentiful guns. The subducted balloon and broad, exposed weather deck of the Mobula lend it an unmistakable silhouette quite unlike that of typical suspended-gondola designs. With its low profile and fore-mounted weapons, the Mobula is adept at coasting at high altitudes and attacking from above or long range. It is relatively weak in close combat vs faster ships.

DescriptionText.En: An unpowered cargo container attached to a balloon.

A grand ship in both opulence and carefully laid out firepower.

FullDescriptionText.En: Drawing inspiration from the much older Goldfish hull design, the grandiose Magnate is often the crown of a privateer's collection. The Mercantile Guild’s signature clusters of round balloons, based on earlier Baronite design and later sold to Yesha, adorn the ship like a crown. With ample guns and gilding, it shines in the sky under the watch of a skilled crew. However, its large size and somewhat complex deck layout also make it a difficult ship for new crew, and a prime target in the sky.

DescriptionText.En: A powerful and balanced assault ship with a rich historic lineage.

FullDescriptionText.En: The venerable Crusader harkens to an older age, exemplifying the Creed of the Fjord Baronies. Primarily designed to replace the even older Spire in guarding against Anglean raids, the stable, vertical design has been abandoned in favor of a long, nimble gun ship. The stately armor is more show than function, relying on overwhelming firepower and ambush rather than survivability. Like the Anglean ships, Baronite design is rumored to come from a source other than the legendary Icarus war.

DescriptionText.En: A deadly ship used in specialized flanking maneuvers with its dual angled heavy guns.

FullDescriptionText.En: While earlier ship designs had been purchased and adapted from the Mercantile Guild, the Judgement pays homage only to its own masters. Utilizing advanced Yeshan metalworking and newly designed balloons, it has been crafted from bow to stern to cut an imposing figure across the horizon. Ships must be wary of being caught in its massive frontal barrage. To the woe of a lone privateer, the Judgement was intended to fly in tight formation. As such, little thought has been given to its exposed flanks.

DescriptionText.En: A strong and sturdy ship that's capable of taking a beating while holding ground.

FullDescriptionText.En: The Angleans hold their secrets in the icy vault of the north. Little is known about their ships, other than they started appearing in the skies at the same time as the Baronies and sparked an arms race between the two factions. The Corsair is the latest entry, presenting massive armor, plentiful guns, and no quarter given. Literally meaning ‘pirate’, this ship is granted to aspiring priveteers raiding for the Republic. With multiple decks and limited visibility, the Corsair can be difficult to crew and pilot.

DescriptionText.En: Agility and firepower combined in a truly unique airship.

FullDescriptionText.En: Lacking the industry of the other factions, Chaladon ships focus on light weight, maneuverability, and a unique flair. Though originally based on Baronite design, the intensive study of lift gas has greatly advanced their ship technology. The Shrike is the pinnacle of these innovations, with a sleek balloon and lightweight frame supporting a pair of heavy guns and engines that almost outweigh the ship itself. Onboard lift gas processing creates an eerie mist about the ship, resulting in either fear or rude jokes.

DescriptionText.En: A swift ship designed to maneuver the deadly and sudden desert storms.

FullDescriptionText.En: Storms break quickly in the desert, swiftly causing destruction and then fading away. This is also the way of the Arashi Stormbreakers. They are quickly constructed with whatever is at hand, without much thought given to safety. Some flights are as short-lived as the desert storms that give them their namesake. Despite their haphazard fragility, they are a well-armed raider powered by engines salvaged from larger ships. This gives them the unique ability to rapidly change direction in combat.

DescriptionText.En: A powerful front-line charger with twin forward guns, an armor-plated beak, and limited maneuverability.

FullDescriptionText.En: The Pyramidion is a modified version of a Yesha warship used in the vanguard of an offensive fleet formation, often backed by a line of smaller striker craft. With its narrow head-on profile and armor-plated balloon, it is a front-line charger of the first order, able to soften a target with concentrated fire from its twin forward guns before ramming for the kill with its reinforced beak. Despite its wide turn radius, it is prized for its overall durability and ability to concentrate fire.

DescriptionText.En: "Are ya steerin', or jest holdin' th' wheel ta keep from fallin' over?"
"Smooth skies do not skillful sailors make."
"When the helm is gone the ship will soon be wrecked."
"This far, no farther."
"The ship that will not obey the helm will have to obey the rocks."
"Sleep when you're dead. Which'll be soon if you don't keep your eyes open."
"It's like a game, see if ye can blow them up afore they hit the ground."
"I'm jest glad 'e's on our side."
"If it moves, shoot it down!"
"It's best to win without fighting, but it's not as much fun."
"I once devised a system with 32 separate bells to sound status alerts...but you couldn't hear it over the captain's bellowing."
"I fixed it! And added a little something special..."
"Eventually one grows accustomed to the flames and constant gunfire. Anticipates them, even, feels strange when it's quiet."
"The dream of human flight is to fly higher, faster, farther, than anyone before. It's about the most dangerous dream you can chase."
"When you're flying through Hell, keep going."
"Float like an aerostat, sting like a BB."
"A merry chase I'll lead...catch me if ye can!"
"Battles are won in the third dimension."
"Hold your fire... Don't speak. Don't breathe. Wait for it..."

NameText.En: On helm, destroy 30 hull armor while unspotted (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "Either put it in the engines, or drink it, but not both at once. Learned that the hard way."
"Throw everything you got at them, and then some."
"INCOMING!"
"I love me a good sparkler show."
"I thought it'd be different up here, all fresh air and birdsong, y'know? Mind, I'm nae complainin'."
"Sometimes she gets this...funny look in her eyes..."
"Nice boots. I sure hope they're up to the job."

NameText.En: Extinguish 5 fires less than 10 seconds after igniting

DescriptionText.En: "I want every gun spotless, gleaming, primed, and ready to fire."

NameText.En: Fully repair 16 balloons less than 10 seconds after receiving damage

DescriptionText.En: "She canna take any more, Cap'n!"

NameText.En: Rebuild 35 parts less than 10 seconds after destruction

DescriptionText.En: "I think I have everything I need on board. Well, I'll improvise."
"The only drawback is its slight tendency to catch fire and explode if left unattended, but other than that it flies like a dream."

NameText.En: Extinguish 30 fires on balloon less than 10 seconds after they start

DescriptionText.En: "I once flew with a captain who liked to make a speech to the crew before every voyage. Gotta fill the balloon with somethin', right?"

NameText.En: As captain, destroy 20 balloons with Carronade (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "Back home we call this an Anglean Rotisserie."

NameText.En: As captain, set 350 fires with Flamethrower (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "I'll repay 'em in kind."

NameText.En: As captain, fully repair 60 hull armor less than 5 seconds after receiving damage (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "Do I have tae do e'erything m'self?"

NameText.En: As captain, rebuild 25 parts with Spanner

DescriptionText.En: "We're not fallin', we're makin' an involuntary emergency descent."

NameText.En: As captain, rebuild 60 balloons less than 10 seconds after destruction (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "Never give up, never go down!"
"Gotta keep movin'."
"Get it up!"
"I don't even know what this bit does. Is't s'posed ta be hangin' off the side like that?"
"I'm a gunner, not an engineer!"
"What goes up must come down, dammit."
"I call it the 'Engineer's Revenge.'"
"The armor's weak spots are not generally well known, but fortunately I happen to have some familiarity with this model."
"A single volley may do just enough damage to push them over the edge. I hope and pray that it does."
"Here's how you keep from getting blown up — go back home to Virna and be a farmer. And even then."

NameText.En: Win 4 matches with no more than 1 death

DescriptionText.En: "There's always a bigger fish."
"I got my thumb down firm on the karmic scales."

NameText.En: Play 6 matches with 3 more kills than deaths

"A good run is better than a bad stand."

DescriptionText.En: "Jes' keep linin' 'em up, an' I'll keep knockin' 'em down."

NameText.En: Play 3 matches with 4 or more kills

NameText.En: Play 6 matches with 3 more kills than deaths

DescriptionText.En: "Drop the sword, but don't let slip the shield."

NameText.En: Win 12 matches against enemy captains all level 8+

DescriptionText.En: "Give 'em hell."

NameText.En: On helm, set 100 parts on fire with Flamethrower (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "You can sail on the sea, and you can sail in the sky, but I never yet saw the boat that could sail on the ground."
"Everyone laughed when Morning Dawn's captain painted her pink, from bowsprit to taffrail...but boy could she sneak up on you in a sunrise."

NameText.En: As captain, destroy 300 parts while unspotted (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "To pull into any port for repairs in such shabby condition would be an outrage to our pride!"
"Sky's full of mercs, drifters, and sailors just out for a paycheck, but as for me, well, I do it all for the folks back home. It's not what's before ye, but what's behind ye that matters most."

DescriptionText.En: "Fire washes away what water cannot."

"They'll never know what hit 'em. So I usually follow up by shouting my name."
"You got anything that needs doing?"
"The heart bleeds more than the skin."
"A pound of prevention is worth several tons of cure."

NameText.En: Extinguish 20 fires on guns with Chemical Spray

DescriptionText.En: "You're jolly good shipmates, but I'd rather not spend eternity with our bones and splinters shook together at the bottom o' some gully, thanks."
"I have some ideas for a few... improvements."
"How shall I put this...we've got our trousers down and our bum-cheeks flapping in the wind here!"

NameText.En: Help a crewmate rebuild 30 hull armor

DescriptionText.En: "By silhouette alone, I can tell you all you want to know about a boat: her class, her condition, what she's got onboard, even the make of her engines and what the pilot's dumped into them."

NameText.En: On helm, destroy 30 parts in CP (crew)

NameText.En: Destroy 2 ships with ramming in CP

DescriptionText.En: "You think it's a kill-or-be-killed world out there? Nah. It's kill-AND-be-killed, and plenty o' both. No one makes it through this life unscathed."

NameText.En: Win 8 DMs with no more than 1 death

DescriptionText.En: "Fools rush in."

NameText.En: Win 8 CPs with no more than 1 death

DescriptionText.En: "WILL. YOU. HOLD. STILL."

"See, a ship's balloon is basically just a big bag of combustable gas. It's honestly a wonder that we fly with these things."

NameText.En: Set 60 fires to balloon in CP

DescriptionText.En: "I gotta notch on me bunk for e'ery ship I's sent down t' th' dust. Wanna see?"
"I love my job."

NameText.En: Play 8 CPs with at least 4 kills

DescriptionText.En: "The chief function of the propellers is to keep the engineer cool. You can tell because whenever they stop spinning, I start to sweat."

NameText.En: Rebuild 10 engines less than 15 seconds after they are destroyed in CP

DescriptionText.En: "It was a constant barrage, everything up in flames, smoke everywhere. But we had to save the hull, and let everything else burn."

NameText.En: Extinguish 40 fires on hull in DM

DescriptionText.En: "If a gun doesn't burst into flame every so often, it just means you're not shooting hard enough."

NameText.En: Extinguish 25 fires on guns in CP

DescriptionText.En: "I never knew an airship could keep flying with so many parts of her missing."

NameText.En: Play 8 DMs with no more than 1 death

DescriptionText.En: "I've had worse."

NameText.En: Play 8 CPs with no more than 1 death

DescriptionText.En: "One more down, the rest of the world to go."
"When the wind kicks up, it feeds the flame, 'til you'd swear the sky itself was afire."
"May the hardest head win."

NameText.En: On helm, destroy 20 ships with Pyramidion (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "A mighty flame followeth a tiny spark."

NameText.En: On helm, set 75 balloons on fire (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "An unassuming vessel may easily be overlooked. This is a mistake."
"Look to yer gun, it spends more time on fire than firing!"
"Look sharp, lads, we've got a lively one!"
"If you can't take the heat, get outta the sky."

DescriptionText.En: "No telling what's hid in this soup."

DescriptionText.En: "Can't hardly see me hand in front of me face, but I can't see yer ugly mug, either, so we'll call it a wash."

"Fill the vanguard with either your bravest warriors or your least favorite."
"Now, this is a case o' the Captain's Special Reserve...I don't break it out for just anyone."
"I almost envy them. What a way to go!"
"Targets neutralized."
"I am sure the cause of military science would be much advanced if I were only accorded a moment's peace to work."
"No small amount of prayer is involved."
"From Hell's heart, I stab at thee."

Play 20 matches with at least 5 kills

DescriptionText.En: "Let them come. Tell 'em I'll be waiting for 'em!"

NameText.En: As captain, destroy 25 hull armor with Field Gun (crew)
As captain, destroy 25 balloons with Mortar (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "Think you won something? It's just the beginning of a long, hard fight to hang on to it."
"My grasp exceeds my reach."

NameText.En: Destroy 25 hull armor at a distance of at least 800m
Destroy 15 balloons at a distance of at least 800m

DescriptionText.En: "Nowt succeeds like excess."
"Sky's falling and the ground's rising up, and here's us crushed in-between."
"It has a short leash, but a sharp bite."

NameText.En: On helm, destroy 50 parts with Carronade in DM (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "They're too busy dyin'."

NameText.En: On helm, destroy 40 ships in CP (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "Someone needs to let the wind out of her bag."
"Why wouldn't you want to fight an unarmed opponent?"
"Spirits fly high with the ship, and both sink together."
"Swiftness will win the day, I think."
"Fire is a good crewman, but a bad captain."

NameText.En: On helm, destroy 40 parts with Flamethrower (crew)
On helm, destroy 40 parts with Incendiary Rounds (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "Come what may, we'll not abandon our post."

NameText.En: On helm, destroy 20 ships with Galleon

DescriptionText.En: "I like my airships like I like my grog...burns going down!"
"Reel 'em in, lads, reel 'em in."
"There is no more chilling sound than the crackling of flame at 500 feet."

NameText.En: Extinguish 75 fires less than 10 seconds after they start

DescriptionText.En: "Next volley'll go through us like a wet paper lantern unless that armor goes back up, and fast."

NameText.En: Play 20 matches with no more than 1 death

DescriptionText.En: "We get in and take what we need, but I've no intention of adding our wrecked carcass to this slag heap. There's nothin' here worth dyin' for."

NameText.En: As captain, capture 20 points with Squid in Refinery

DescriptionText.En: "You may speak to me so while we stand here on firm ground, but let us take to the air and see who's the cleverer."

NameText.En: As captain, win 5 matches with Goldfish in Duel

DescriptionText.En: "This is a dangerous area, somebody really ought to clean it up. All sorts of things could happen."

NameText.En: Spot 12 ships at a distance of at least 750m in Refinery

DescriptionText.En: "Ruffian! Cur! To strike while my back is turned — blackguard!"

NameText.En: Win 8 matches in Duel at Dawn

DescriptionText.En: "Safety...oh, I'd say eleventh or so?"

NameText.En: Spot 12 ships at a distance of at least 750m in Refinery

DescriptionText.En: "All contests are rigged. Only in death are all folk equal — ay, some say that's it's chief virtue."
"Every sailor's got two eyes/One for the deck and one for the skies."

NameText.En: On helm, destroy 10 ships inside a cloud (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "As the captain goes down with the ship, so does the ship go down with the captain."

NameText.En: Win 10 matches with no more than 1 death against enemy captains all level 8+

DescriptionText.En: "Can't see what I hit, but something gave a yelp."

NameText.En: Spot 10 ships at distance of at least 1000m

"Sometimes the trick to seeing is not seeing."

NameText.En: Spot 10 ships at a distance of at least 1000m

DescriptionText.En: "She was a bargain. A real good bargain, I'd wager."
"The wind cannot shake a mountain."
"Airship, fire, not good."
"I think I see your problem right here..."
"Time for a dramatic exit!"
"YAAAAAHHHHHH!"
"Gravity weights for no man."
"Make an end."

NameText.En: As captain, destroy 35 ships with Mortar (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "Doin' nothin' is doin' ill."
"Eternal peace lasts until the next war."
"The bigger they are...well, the longer it takes to kill them, I suppose. I mean, that's just common sense."

NameText.En: Win 20 matches against enemy captains all level 8+

DescriptionText.En: "You can breach a city wall with a chisel and patience."

NameText.En: Win 20 matches against enemy captains all level 8+

DescriptionText.En: "Which is stronger, the will to kill, or the will to live? Ah, but which is easier to accomplish?"

NameText.En: Win 20 matches against enemy captains all level 8+

DescriptionText.En: "Wrenches at the ready, we're in for a bumpy ride."

NameText.En: On helm, fully repair 200 engines less than 5 seconds after receiving damage (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "Keep those guns and propellers spinning!"
"Captain knows how to put a ship through her paces, that's for sure."
"They never saw us comin', and they won't see us goin', neither."

NameText.En: On helm, destroy 15 ships while unspotted in DM (crew)

DescriptionText.En: "Didn't see that one comin', did ya?"

NameText.En: Destroy 75 parts while unspotted in DM

DescriptionText.En: "I fear it will take us some time to recover from this."
